# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spanning-tree-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] A **network bridge** is a computer networking device that creates a single, aggregate network from multiple communication networks or network segments.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] This function is called **network bridging**.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Routing allows multiple networks to communicate independently and yet remain separate, whereas bridging connects two separate networks as if they were a single network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] In the OSI model, bridging is performed in the data link layer (layer 2).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] If one or more segments of the bridged network are wireless, the device is known as a **wireless bridge**.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The main types of network bridging technologies are simple bridging, multiport bridging, and learning or transparent bridging.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Transparent bridging uses a table called the *forwarding information base* to control the forwarding of frames between network segments.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The table starts empty and entries are added as the bridge receives frames.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] If a destination address entry is not found in the table, the frame is forwarded to all other ports of the bridge, flooding the frame to all segments except the one from which it was received.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] By means of these flooded frames, a host on the destination network will respond and a forwarding database entry will be created.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Both source and destination addresses are used in this process: source addresses are recorded in entries in the table, while destination addresses are looked up in the table and matched to the proper segment to send the frame to.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) originally developed the technology in 1983 and introduced the LANBridge 100 that implemented it in 1986.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] In the context of a two-port bridge, the forwarding information base can be seen as a filtering database.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] A bridge reads a frame's destination address and decides to either forward or filter.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] If the bridge determines that the destination host is on another segment on the network, it forwards the frame to that segment.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] If the destination address belongs to the same segment as the source address, the bridge filters the frame, preventing it from reaching the other network where it is not needed.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Transparent bridging can also operate over devices with more than two ports.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] As an example, consider a bridge connected to three hosts, A, B, and C.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] A is connected to bridge port 1, B is connected to bridge port 2, C is connected to bridge port 3.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] A sends a frame addressed to B to the bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The bridge examines the source address of the frame and creates an address and port number entry for host *A* in its forwarding table.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The bridge examines the destination address of the frame and does not find it in its forwarding table so it floods (broadcasts) it to all other ports: 2 and 3.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Host C examines the destination address and ignores the frame as it does not match with its address.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Host B recognizes a destination address match and generates a response to A.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] On the return path, the bridge adds an address and port number entry for B to its forwarding table.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The bridge already has A's address in its forwarding table so it forwards the response only to port 1.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Host C or any other hosts on port 3 are not burdened with the response.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Two-way communication is now possible between A and B without any further flooding to the network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Now, if A sends a frame addressed to C, the same procedure will be used, but this time the bridge will not create a new forwarding-table entry for A's address/port because it has already done so.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Bridging is called *transparent* when the frame format and its addressing aren't changed substantially.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] *Non-transparent* bridging is required especially when the frame addressing schemes on both sides of a bridge are not compatible with each other, e.g. between ARCNET with local addressing and Ethernet using IEEE MAC addresses, requiring translation.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] However, most often such incompatible networks are routed in between, not bridged.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] A simple bridge connects two network segments, typically by operating transparently and deciding on a frame-by-frame basis whether or not to forward from one network to the other.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] A store and forward technique is typically used so, as part of forwarding, the frame integrity is verified on the source network and CSMA/CD delays are accommodated on the destination network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] In contrast to repeaters which simply extend the maximum span of a segment, bridges only forward frames that are required to cross the bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Additionally, bridges reduce collisions by creating a separate collision domain on either side of the bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] A multiport bridge connects multiple networks and operates transparently to decide on a frame-by-frame basis *whether* to forward traffic.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Additionally, a multiport bridge must decide *where* to forward traffic.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Like the simple bridge, a multiport bridge typically uses store and forward operation.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The multiport bridge function serves as the basis for network switches.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The forwarding information base stored in content-addressable memory (CAM) is initially empty.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] For each received Ethernet frame the switch learns from the frame's source MAC address and adds this together with an interface identifier to the forwarding information base.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The switch then forwards the frame to the interface found in the CAM based on the frame's destination MAC address.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] If the destination address is unknown the switch sends the frame out on all interfaces (except the ingress interface).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] This behavior is called unicast flooding.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Once a bridge learns the addresses of its connected nodes, it forwards data link layer frames using a layer-2 forwarding method.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Cut through: the switch starts forwarding after the frame's destination address is received.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] There is no error checking with this method.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] When the outgoing port is busy at the time, the switch falls back to store-and-forward operation.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Also, when the egress port is running at a faster data rate than the ingress port, store-and-forward is usually used.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Fragment free: a method that attempts to retain the benefits of both store and forward and cut through.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Fragment free checks the first 64 bytes of the frame, where addressing information is stored.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] According to Ethernet specifications, collisions should be detected during the first 64 bytes of the frame, so frame transmissions that are aborted because of a collision will not be forwarded.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Error checking of the actual data in the packet is left for the end device.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Adaptive switching: a method of automatically selecting between the other three modes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] If network bridges are connected in a way that forms redundant paths or mesh loops, broadcast frames loop through the network indefinitely, bringing it to a halt.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] This situation must be mitigated using a spanning tree protocol or a more intelligent forwarding algorithm like Shortest Path Bridging or TRILL.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] A spanning tree protocol is a distributed algorithm that organizes active ports in way to form a spanning tree, where there is only one usable path between any two nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] Shortest Path Bridging (SPB), specified in the IEEE 802.1aq standard and based on Dijkstra's algorithm, is a computer networking technology intended to simplify the creation and configuration of networks, while enabling multipath routing.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] It is a proposed replacement for Spanning Tree Protocol which blocks any redundant paths that could result in a switching loop.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] SPB allows all paths to be active with multiple equal-cost paths.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] SPB also increases the number of VLANs allowed on a layer-2 network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) is the successor to Spanning Tree Protocol, both having been created by the same person, Radia Perlman.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The catalyst for TRILL was an event at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center which began on 13 November 2002.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/bridging-networking] The concept of Rbridges [sic] was first proposed to the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers in the year 2004, who in 2005 rejected what came to be known as TRILL, and in the years 2006 through 2012 devised an incompatible variation known as Shortest Path Bridging.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] A **broadcast domain** is a logical division of a computer network, in which all nodes can reach each other by broadcast at the data link layer.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] A broadcast domain can be within the same LAN segment or it can be bridged to other LAN segments.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] In terms of current popular technologies, any computer connected to the same Ethernet repeater or switch is a member of the same broadcast domain.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Further, any computer connected to the same set of interconnected switches or repeaters is a member of the same broadcast domain.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Routers and other network-layer devices form boundaries between broadcast domains.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] The notion of a broadcast domain can be compared with a collision domain, which would be all nodes on the same set of inter-connected repeaters and divided by switches and network bridges.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Collision domains are generally smaller than and contained within broadcast domains.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] While some data-link-layer devices are able to divide the collision domains, broadcast domains are only divided by network-layer devices such as routers or layer-3 switches.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Separating VLANs divides broadcast domains as well.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] The distinction between broadcast and collision domains comes about because simple Ethernet and similar systems use a shared medium for communication.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] In simple Ethernet (without switches or bridges), data frames are transmitted to all other nodes on a network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Each receiving node checks the destination address of each frame and simply ignores any frame not addressed to its own MAC address or the broadcast address.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Switches act as buffers, receiving and analyzing the frames from each connected network segment.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Frames destined for nodes connected to the originating segment are not forwarded by the switch.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Frames destined for a specific node on a different segment are sent only to that segment.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Only broadcast frames are forwarded to all other segments.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] This reduces unnecessary traffic and collisions.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] In such a switched network, transmitted frames may not be received by all other reachable nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Nominally, only broadcast frames will be received by all other nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Collisions are localized to the physical-layer network segment they occur on.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Thus, the broadcast domain is the entire inter-connected layer-2 network, and the segments connected to each switch or bridge port are each a collision domain.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] To clarify; repeaters do not divide collision domains but switches do.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] This means that since switches have become commonplace, collision domains are isolated to the specific segment between the switch port and the connected node.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Full-duplex segments, or links, don't form a collision domain as there is a dedicated channel between each transmitter and receiver, eliminating the possibility of collisions.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] With a sufficiently sophisticated switch, it is possible to create a network in which a broadcast domain is strictly controlled.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] One implementation of this concept is a private VLAN.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Another implementation is possible with Linux and iptables.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] One analogy is that by creating multiple VLANs, the number of broadcast domains increases, but the size of each broadcast domain decreases.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] This is because a VLAN defines a broadcast domain.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] This is achieved by designating one or more *provider* nodes, either by MAC address or switch port.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Broadcast frames are allowed to originate from these sources and are sent to all other nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Broadcast frames from all other sources are directed only to the provider nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Traffic from other sources not destined to the provider nodes (peer-to-peer traffic) is blocked.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] The result is a network based on a nominally shared transmission system; like Ethernet, but in which client nodes cannot communicate with each other, only with the provider.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/broadcast-domain] Allowing direct data link layer communication between client nodes exposes the network to various security attacks, such as ARP spoofing.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB is designed to replace the older Spanning Tree Protocols: IEEE 802.1D STP, IEEE 802.1w RSTP, and IEEE 802.1s MSTP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] It is designed to preserve the plug-and-play nature that established Ethernet as the de facto protocol at layer 2.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The technology provides VLANs on native Ethernet infrastructures using a link-state protocol to advertise both topology and VLAN membership.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Packets are encapsulated at the edge either in MAC-in-MAC per IEEE 802.1ah or tagged per IEEE 802.1Q or IEEE 802.1ad and transported only to other members of VLAN.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Unicast, multicast, and broadcast are supported and all routing is on symmetric shortest paths.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The control plane is based on the Intermediate System to Intermediate System (IS-IS) routing protocol, leveraging a small number of extensions defined in RFC 6329.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] On 4 March 2006 the working group posted 802.1aq draft 0.1.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In March 2012 the IEEE approved the 802.1aq standard.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In May 2013, the first public multivendor interoperability was demonstrated as SPB served as the backbone for Interop 2013 in Las Vegas.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In 2013 and 2014 SPB was used to build the InteropNet backbone with only one-tenth the resources of prior years.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] During Interop 2014 SPB was used as the backbone protocol which can enable software-defined networking (SDN) functionalities.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The 2014 Winter Olympics were the first "fabric-enabled" Games using SPB "IEEE 802.1aq" technology.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] During the games this fabric network could handle up to 54 Tbit/s of traffic.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The Intermediate System to Intermediate System (IS-IS) protocol, as defined in the IETF proposed standard RFC 6329, is used as the control plane for SPB.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB requires no state machine or other substantive changes to IS-IS, and simply requires a new Network Layer Protocol Identifier (NLPID) and set of TLVs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB allows for shortest-path forwarding in a mesh-connected Ethernet network utilizing multiple equal-cost paths.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This permits SPB to support large Layer 2 topologies, with faster convergence, and improved use of the mesh topology when compared to networks configured with Spanning Tree Protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB augments IS-IS with a small number of TLVs and sub-TLVs, and supports two Ethernet encapsulating data paths, IEEE 802.1ad provider bridges (PB) and IEEE 802.1ah Provider Backbone Bridges (PBB).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB is designed to run in parallel with other network-layer protocols such as IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Standards mandate that the failure of two nodes to establish an SPB adjacency will not have a collateral impact, such as the rejection of an adjacency for other network-layer protocols (e.g., OSPF).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] 802.1aq has been designed to operate in parallel with other network layer protocols such as IPv4 and IPv6; therefore, failure of two nodes to establish an SPB adjacency will not cause network layer protocols to also reject an adjacency.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] RFC 6328 assigns 802.1aq the Network Layer Protocol ID (NLPID) value 0xC1.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This NLPID is used by SPB Bridges to indicate their ability to form adjacencies and operate as part of an 802.1aq domain.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] 802.1aq frames flow on adjacencies that advertise this NLPID in both directions, and nodes regard an adjacency that has not been advertised in both directions as non-existent (with infinite link metric).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] 802.1aq augments the normal IIH PDU with three new TLVs, which like all other SPB TLVs, travel within *Multi-Topology TLVs*, therefore allowing multiple logical instances of SPB within a single IS-IS protocol instance.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB can use many VIDs, agreeing on which VIDs are used for which purposes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The IIH PDUs carry a digest of all the used VIDs, referred to as the *Multiple Spanning Tree Configuration TLV* which uses a common and compact encoding reused from IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] For the purposes of loop prevention SPB neighbors may also support a mechanism to verify that the contents of their topology databases are synchronized.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Exchanging digests of SPB topology information, using the optional *SPB-Digest sub-TLV*, allows nodes to compare information and take specific action where a mismatch in topology is indicated.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Finally, SPB needs to know which shortest path tree (SPT) sets are being used by which VIDs, and this is carried in the *Base VLAN Identifiers TLV*.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] All SPB nodal information extensions travel within a new *Multi-Topology (MT) capability TLV*.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] There can be one or many MT-Capability TLVs present, depending on the amount of information that needs to be carried.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The *SPB Instance sub-TLV* gives the Shortest Path Source ID (SPSourceID) for this node or topology instance.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This is used in the formation of multicast destination addresses (DAs) for frames originating from this node or instance.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] There are multiple ECT algorithms defined for SPB and additional algorithms may be defined in the future, including but not limited to ECMP- or hash-based behaviors and (*,G) Multicast trees.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] These algorithms will use this optional TLV to define new algorithm parametric data.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] For tie-breaking parameters, there are two broad classes of algorithms: one that uses nodal data to break ties and one that uses link data to break ties.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The *SPB Instance Opaque Equal cost Tree Algorithm TLV* is used to associate opaque tie-breaking data with a node.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The *SPB Link Metric sub-TLV* occurs within the Multi-Topology Intermediate System Neighbor TLV or within the Extended IS Reachability TLV.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] *SPB Adjacency Opaque Equal Cost Tree Algorithm TLV* also occurs within the Multi-Topology Intermediate System TLV or the Extended IS Reachability TLV.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Where this sub-TLV is not present for an IS-IS adjacency, that adjacency will not carry SPB traffic for the given topology instance.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The *SPBM Service Identifier and Unicast Address TLV* is used to introduce service group membership on the originating node or to advertise an additional B-MAC unicast address present on, or reachable by the node.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The *SPBV MAC Address TLV* is the IS-IS sub-TLV used for advertisement of group MAC addresses in SPBV mode.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Shortest Path Bridging-VID (SPBV) and Shortest Path Bridging-MAC (SPBM) are two operating modes of 802.1aq.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBM offers emulation of a transparent Ethernet LAN segment.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The carrier-space equivalent of this application is the delivery of Ethernet VPN services to Enterprises over common carrier infrastructure.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The required attributes are fundamentally the same; complete transparency for customer Ethernet services (both point-to-point and LAN), and complete isolation between one customer's traffic and that of all other customers.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] A further consequence of SPBM's transparency in both data plane and control plane is that it delivers the MEF 6.1 service set.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] It also provides the carrier with the toolkit to support geo-redundant broadband backhaul; in these applications, many DSLAMs or other access equipment must be backhauled to multiple Broadband Remote Access Server (BRAS) sites, with application-determined binding of sessions to a BRAS.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] However, DSLAMs must not be allowed to communicate with each other, because carriers then lose the ability to control peer-to-peer connectivity.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] MEF E-TREE does just this, and further provides an efficient multicast fabric for the distribution of IPTV.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] These two models are selected by specifying properties of the service at the edge, which affect the transit node decisions on multicast state installation.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This allows for a trade-off to be made between optimum transit replication points (with their larger state costs) vs. reduced core state (but much more traffic) of the head-end replication model.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] These selections can be different for different members of the same Individual Service ID (I-SID), allowing different trade-offs to be made for different members.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Figure 5 below is a quick way to understand what SPBM is doing on the scale of the entire network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Figure 5 shows how a 7-member E-LAN is created from the edge membership information and the deterministic distributed calculation of per source, per service trees with transit replication.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Head-end replication is not shown as it is trivial and simply uses the existing unicast FIBs to forward copies serially to the known other receivers.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] 802.1aq builds on all existing Ethernet operations, administration and management (OA&M).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since 802.1aq ensures that its unicast and multicast packets for a given virtual LAN (VLAN) follow the same forward and reverse path and use completely standard 802 encapsulations, all the methods of IEEE 802.1ag and Y.1731 operate unchanged on an 802.1aq network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] 802.1aq is the IEEE-sanctioned link state Ethernet control plane for all IEEE VLANs covered in IEEE 802.1Q.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The Shortest Path Bridging virtual local area network identifier (VLAN ID) or Shortest Path Bridging VID (SPBV) provides a capability that is backward compatible with spanning tree technologies.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The SPBM provides additional values that use Provider Backbone Bridge (PBB) capabilities.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB (the generic term for both) combines an Ethernet data path (either IEEE 802.1Q in the case of SPBV, or PBBs per IEEE 802.1ah in the case of SPBM) with an IS-IS link state control protocol running between Shortest Path bridges (Network-to-network interface (NNI) links).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The link state protocol is used to discover and advertise the network topology and compute SPTs from all bridges in the SPT Region.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In SPBM, the backbone MAC (B-MAC) addresses of the participating nodes and also the service membership information for interfaces to non-participating devices (User–network interface (UNI) ports) is distributed.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Topology data is then input to a calculation engine, which computes symmetric shortest path trees based on minimum cost from each participating node to all other participating nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In SPBV, these trees provide a shortest path tree where individual MAC address can be learned and group address membership can be distributed.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In SPBM, the shortest path trees are then used to populate forwarding tables for each participating node's individual B-MAC addresses and for group addresses; Group multicast trees are subtrees of the default shortest path tree formed by (source, group) pairing.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Depending on the topology, several different equal-cost multi-path trees are possible and SPB supports multiple algorithms per IS-IS instance.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In SPB as with other link-state-based protocols, the computations are done in a distributed fashion.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Each node computes the Ethernet-compliant forwarding behavior independently based on a normally synchronized common view of the network and UNI ports.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Ethernet filtering Database (or forwarding) tables are populated locally to independently and deterministically implement its portion of the network forwarding behavior.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The two different flavors of data path give rise to two slightly different versions of this protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] One (SPBM) is intended where complete isolation of many separate instances of client LANs and their associated device MAC addresses is desired, and it therefore uses a full encapsulation (MAC-in-MAC a.k.a.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The other (SPBV) is intended where such isolation of client device MAC addresses is not necessary, and it reuses only the existing VLAN tag on participating NNI links.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Chronologically, SPBV came first, with the project originally being conceived to address scalability and convergence of MSTP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] At the time the specification for PBB was progressing, it became apparent that leveraging both the PBB data plane and a link state control plane would significantly extend Ethernet's capabilities and applications.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Provider Link State Bridging (PLSB) was a straw man proposal brought to the IEEE 802.1aq Shortest Path Bridging Working Group, to provide a concrete example of such a system.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] As IEEE 802.1aq standardization progressed, some of the detailed mechanisms proposed by PLSB were replaced by functional equivalents, but all of the key concepts embodied in PLSB were carried forward into the standard.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] A primary feature of Shortest Path Bridging is the ability to use link-state IS-IS to learn network topology.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In SPBV the mechanism used to identify the tree is to use a different Shortest Path VLAN ID (SPVID) for each source bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The IS-IS topology is used both to allocate unique SPVIDs and to enable shortest path forwarding for individual and group addresses.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Originally targeted for small, low-configuration networks, SPB grew into a larger project encompassing the latest provider control plane for SPBV and harmonizing the concepts of Ethernet's data plane.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB defines a shortest path *region* which is the boundary of the shortest path topology and the rest of the VLAN topology, which may be any number of legacy bridges.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPB operates by learning the SPB-capable bridges and growing the *region* to include the SPB-capable bridges that have the same Base VID and MSTID configuration digest (Allocation of VIDs for SPB purposes).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBV builds shortest-path trees that support loop prevention and optionally support loop mitigation on the SPVID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBV builds shortest-path trees but also interworks with legacy bridges running Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol and Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (MSTP).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBV uses techniques from MSTP regions to interwork with non-SPT regions, behaving logically as a large distributed bridge as viewed from outside the region.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBV supports shortest path trees, but SPBV also builds a spanning tree, which is computed from the link state database and uses the Base VID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This means that SPBV can use this traditional spanning tree for computation of the common and internal spanning tree (CIST).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The CIST is the default tree used to interwork with other legacy bridges.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] It also serves as a fallback spanning tree if there are configuration problems with SPBV.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBV has been designed to manage a moderate number of bridges.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBV differs from SPBM in that MAC addresses are learned on all bridges that lie on the shortest path, and shared VLAN learning is used since destination MACs may be associated with multiple SPVIDs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBV learns all MACs it forwards, even outside the SPBV region.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Shortest Path Bridging-MAC (SPBM) reuses the PBB data plane, which does not require that the Backbone Core Bridges (BCB) learn encapsulated client addresses.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] At the edge of the network, the C-MAC (client) addresses are learned.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] SPBM is very similar to Provider Link State Bridging (PLSB), using the same data and control planes, but the format and contents of the control messages in PLSB are not compatible.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Ethernet destination addresses (from UNI port attached devices) perform learning over the logical LAN and are forwarded to the appropriate participating B-MAC address to reach the far-end Ethernet destination.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In this manner, Ethernet MAC addresses are never looked up in the core of an IEEE 802.1aq network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] When comparing SPBM to PBB, the behavior is almost identical to a PBB IEEE 802.1ah network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] PBB does not specify how B-MAC addresses are learned, and PBB may use a spanning tree to control the B-VLAN.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In SPBM, the main difference is that B-MAC addresses are distributed or computed in the control plane, eliminating the B-MAC learning in PBB.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Also, SPBM ensures that the route followed is the shortest path tree.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The forward and reverse paths used for unicast and multicast traffic in an IEEE 802.1aq network are symmetric.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This symmetry permits IEEE 802.1ag Continuity Fault Management (CFM) to operate unchanged for SPBV and SPBM and has desirable properties with respect to time distribution protocols such as Precision Time Protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Group address and unknown destination individual frames are optimally transmitted to only members of the same Ethernet service.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] IEEE 802.1aq supports the creation of thousands of logical Ethernet services in the form of E-LINE, E-LAN or E-TREE constructs, which are formed between non-participating logical ports of the IEEE 802.1aq network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] These group address packets are encapsulated with a PBB header, which indicates the source participating address in the SA while the DA indicates the locally significant group address this frame should be forwarded on, and the source bridge where the frame originated.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since the group address computation produces shortest path trees, there is only ever one copy of a multicast packet on any given link.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since only bridges on the shortest path between participating logical ports create FDB state, the multicast makes efficient use of network resources.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The actual group address forwarding operation operates more or less identically to classical Ethernet; the backbone destination address (B-DA)+ backbone VLAN identifier (B-VID) combination is looked up to find the egress set of next hops.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The only difference compared with classical Ethernet is that reverse learning is disabled for participating bridge backbone media access control (B-MAC) addresses and is replaced with an ingress check and discard (when the frame arrives on an incoming interface from an unexpected source).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Learning is, however, implemented at the edges of the SPBM multicast tree to learn the B-MAC to MAC address relationship for correct individual frame encapsulation in the reverse direction (as packets arrive over the interface).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Properly implemented, an IEEE 802.1aq network can support up to 1000 participating bridges and provide tens of thousands of layer-2 E-LAN services to Ethernet devices.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This can be done by simply configuring the ports facing the Ethernet devices to indicate they are members of a given service.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] As new members come and go, the IS-IS protocol will advertise the I-SID membership changes and the computations will grow or shrink the trees in the participating node network as necessary to maintain the efficient multicast property for that service.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] IEEE 802.1aq has the property that only the point of attachment of a service needs configuration when a new attachment point comes or goes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The trees produced by the computations will automatically be extended or pruned as necessary to maintain connectivity.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Failure recovery is driven by IS-IS with the link failure being advertised and new computations being performed, resulting in new FDB tables.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since no Ethernet addresses are advertised or known by IS-IS, there is no re-learning required by the SPBM core and its learned encapsulations are unaffected by a transit node or link failure.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Link failure detection may be improved using IEEE 802.1ag Continuity Check Protocol (CCP), which tests link status and reports a failure to the IS-IS protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This allows much faster failure detection than is possible using the IS-IS hello message loss mechanisms.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Both SPBV and SPBM inherit the rapid convergence of a link-state control plane.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] A special attribute of SPBM is its ability to rebuild multicast trees in a similar time to unicast convergence, because it substitutes computation for signaling.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] When an SPBM bridge has performed the computations on a topology database, it knows whether it is on the shortest path between a root and one or more leaves of the SPT and can install state accordingly.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Convergence is not gated by incremental discovery of a bridge's place on a multicast tree by the use of separate signaling transactions.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] However, SPBM on a node does not operate completely independently of its peers and enforces agreement on the current network topology with its peers.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This very efficient mechanism uses the exchange of a single digest of link state covering the entire network view, and does not need agreement on each path to each root individually.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The result is that the volume of messaging exchanged to converge the network is in proportion to the incremental change in topology and not the number of multicast trees in the network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] A simple link event that may change many trees is communicated by signaling the link event only; the consequent tree construction is performed by local computation at each node.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The addition of a single service access point to a service instance involves only the announcement of the I-SID, regardless of the number of trees.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Similarly, the removal of a bridge, which might involve the rebuilding of hundreds to thousands of trees, is signaled only with a few link-state updates.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In a multi-chassis link aggregation group environment, multiple switch chassis appear as a single switch to the SPB control plane, and multiple links between pairs of chassis appear as an aggregate link.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In this context, a single link or node failure is not seen by the control plane and is handled locally, potentially resulting in sub-50 ms recovery times.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Three animated GIFs in this section help to show the behavior of 802.1aq.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The first of these gifs, shown in Figure 5, demonstrates the routing in a 66-node network where we have created a 7-member E-LAN using ISID 100.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In this example, we show the equal cost tree (ECT) created from each member to reach all of the other members.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] We cycle through each member to show the full set of trees created for this service.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] We pause at one point to show the symmetry of routing between two of the nodes and emphasize it with a red line.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In each case, the source of the tree is highlighted with a small purple V.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The second of these animated GIFs, shown in Figure 6, demonstrates 8 ECT paths in the same 66-node network as Figure 4.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In each subsequent animated frame, the same source is used (in purple) but a different destination is shown (in yellow).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] For each frame, all of the shortest paths are shown superimposed between the source and destination.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] When two shortest paths traverse the same hop, the thickness of the lines being drawn is increased.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In addition to the 66-node network, a small multi-level data center style network is also shown with sources and destinations both within the servers (at the bottom) and from servers to the router layer at the top.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This animation helps to show the diversity of the ECT being produced.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The last of these animated GIFs, shown in Figure 7, demonstrates source-destination ECT paths using all 16 of the standard algorithms currently defined.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Sixteen equal cost multi-tree (ECMT) paths are initially defined; however, there are many more possible.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] ECMT in an IEEE 802.1aq network is more predictable than with internet protocol (IP) or multiprotocol label switching (MPLS) because of symmetry between the forward and reverse paths.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The choice as to which ECMT path will be used is therefore an operator-assigned head-end decision, while it is a local or hashing decision with IP/MPLS.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Other ECMT algorithms are created by simply using known permutations of the BridgePriority and SysIDs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] For example, the second defined ECMT algorithm uses the path with the minimum of the inverse of the BridgeIdentifier and can be thought of as taking the path with the maximum node identifier.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] For SPBM, each permutation is instantiated as a distinct B-VID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The upper limit of multipath permutations is gated by the number of B-VIDs delegated to 802.1aq operation, a maximum of 4094, although the number of useful path permutations would only require a fraction of the available B-VID space.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Fourteen additional ECMT algorithms are defined with different bit masks applied to the BridgeIdentifiers.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since the BridgeIdentifier includes a priority field, it is possible to adjust the ECMT behavior by changing BridgePriority.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] A service is assigned to a given ECMT B-VID at the edge of the network by configuration.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] As a result, non-participating packets associated with that service are encapsulated with the VID associated with the desired ECMT end-to-end path.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] All individual and group address traffic associated with this service will therefore use the proper ECMT B-VID and be carried symmetrically end to end on the proper equal cost multi path.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Essentially, the operator decides which services go in which ECMT paths, unlike a hashing solution used in other systems, such as IP/MPLS.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Trees can support hashing associated with link aggregation (LAG) groups within a tree branch segment.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This symmetric and end-to-end ECMT behavior gives IEEE 802.1aq a predictable behavior, and offline engineering tools can model data flows.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The behavior is also advantageous to networks where one-way delay measurements are important.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The one-way delay can be computed as half the round-trip delay.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Such computations are used by time distribution protocols such as IEEE 1588.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Shown above are three figures [5,6,7] which show 8 and 16 equal cost tree (ECT) behavior in different network topologies.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] These are composites of screen captures of an 802.1aq network emulator and show the source in purple, the destination in yellow, and then all the computed and available shortest paths in pink.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The thicker the line, the more shortest paths use that link.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The animations show three different networks and a variety of source and destination pairs, which continually change to help visualize what is happening.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The equal cost tree (ECT) algorithms can be almost extended through the use of OPAQUE data, which allows extensions beyond the base 16 algorithms more or less infinitely.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] It is expected that other standards groups or vendors will produce variations on the currently defined algorithms with behaviors suited for different network styles.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] It is expected that numerous shared tree models will also be defined, as will hop-by-hop hash-based equal-cost multi-path (ECMP) style behaviors, all defined by a VID and an algorithm that every node agrees to run.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] 802.1aq does not spread traffic on a hop-by-hop basis.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Instead, 802.1aq allows assignment of a Service ID (ISID) to a VLAN ID (VID) at the edge of the network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] A VID will correspond to exactly one of the possible sets of shortest path nodes in the network and will never stray from that routing.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] If there are 10 or so shortest paths between different nodes, it is possible to assign different services to different paths and to know that the traffic for a given service will follow exactly the given path.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In this manner, traffic can easily be assigned to the desired shortest path.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In the event that one of the paths becomes overloaded, it is possible to move some services off that shortest path by reassigning those services' ISID to a different, less loaded, VID at the edges of the network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The deterministic nature of the routing simplifies offline prediction, computation and experimentation with network loading since actual routes are not dependent on the contents of the packet headers except for the VID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Figure 4 shows four different equal-cost paths between nodes 7 and 5.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] An operator can achieve a relatively good balance of traffic across the cut between nodes [0 and 2] and [1 and 3] by assigning the services at nodes 7 and 5 to one of the four desired VIDs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Using more than 4 equal cost tree (ECT) paths in the network will likely allow all 4 of these paths to be used.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Balance can also be achieved between nodes 6 and 4 in a similar manner.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In the event that an operator does not wish to manually assign services to shortest paths, it is a simple matter for a switch vendor to allow a simple hash of the ISID to one of the available VIDS to give a degree of non-engineered spreading.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] For example, the ISID modulo the number of ECT-VIDs could be used to decide on the actual relative VID to use.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In the event that the ECT paths are not sufficiently diverse, the operator has the option of adjusting the inputs to the distributed ECT algorithms to apply attraction or repulsion from a given node by adjusting that node's Bridge Priority.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This can be experimented with via offline tools until the desired routes are achieved, at which point the bias can be applied to the real network and then ISIDs can be moved to the resulting routes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Looking at the animations in Figure 6 shows the diversity available for traffic engineering in a 66-node network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In this animation, there are 8 ECT paths available from each highlighted source to destination and therefore services could be assigned to 8 different pools based on the VID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] One such initial assignment in Figure 6 could therefore be (ISID modulo 8) with subsequent fine tuning as required.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] We will work through SPBM behavior on a small example, with emphasis on the shortest-path trees for unicast and multicast.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The network shown in Figure 1 consists of 8 participating nodes numbered 0 through 7.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] These would be switches or routers running the IEEE 802.1aq protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Each of the 8 participating nodes has a number of adjacencies numbered 1..5.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] These would likely correspond to interface indexes, or possibly port numbers.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since 802.1aq does not support parallel interfaces, each interface corresponds to an adjacency.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The network has a fully meshed inner core of four nodes (0..3) and then four outer nodes (4,5,6 and 7), each dual-homed onto a pair of inner core nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Normally, when nodes come from the factory, they have a MAC address assigned, which becomes a node identifier, but for the purpose of this example, we will assume that the nodes have MAC addresses of the form 00:00:00:00:N:00 where N is the node id (0..7) from Figure 1.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The IS-IS protocol runs on all the links shown since they are between participating nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The IS-IS hello protocol has a few additions for 802.1aq, including information about backbone VIDs to be used by the protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] We will assume that the operator has chosen to use backbone VIDs 101 and 102 for this instance of 802.1aq on this network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The node will use its MAC addresses as the IS-IS SysId and join a single IS-IS level and exchange link-state packets (LSPs in IS-IS terminology).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The LSPs will contain node information and link information such that every node will learn the full topology of the network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since we have not specified any link weights in this example, the IS-IS protocol will pick a default link metric for all links; therefore, all routing will be minimum hop count.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] After topology discovery, the next step is distributed calculation of the unicast routes for both ECMP VIDs and population of the unicast forwarding tables (FIBs).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Consider the route from Node 7 to Node 5: there are a number of equal-cost paths.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] 802.1aq specifies how to choose two of them: the first is referred to as the Low PATH ID path.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This is the path that has the minimum node id on it.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In this case, the Low PATH ID path is the 7->0->1->5 path (as shown in red in Figure 2).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Therefore, each node on that path will create a forwarding entry toward the MAC address of node five using the first ECMP VID 101.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Conversely, 802.1aq specifies a second ECMP tie-breaking algorithm called High PATH ID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This is the path with the maximum node identifier on it and in the example is the 7->2->3->5 path (shown in blue in Figure 2).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The intermediate nodes will also produce consistent results, so, for example, node 1 will have the following entries.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] If we had an attached non-participating device at Node 7 talking to a non-participating device at Node 5 (for example, Device A talks to Device C in Figure 3), they would communicate over one of these shortest paths with a MAC-in-MAC encapsulated frame.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The MAC header on any of the NNI links would show an outer source address of 00:00:00:70:00, an outer destination address of 00:00:00:50:00 and a BVID of either 101 or 102, depending on which has been chosen for this set of non-participating ports/vids.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The header, once inserted at node 7 when received from node A, would not change on any of the links until it egressed back to non-participating Device C at Node 5.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] All participating devices would do a simple DA+VID lookup to determine the outgoing interface, and would also check that the incoming interface is the proper next hop for the packet's SA+VID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] 00:00:00:07:00 are never learned but are advertised by IS-IS as the node's SysId.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Unicast forwarding to a non-participating client (e.g., A, B, C, D from Figure 3) address is, of course, only possible when the first hop participating node (e.g., 7) is able to know which last hop participating node (e.g., 5) is attached to the desired non-participating node (e.g., C).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since this information is not advertised by IEEE 802.1aq, it has to be learned.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The mechanism for learning is identical to IEEE 802.1ah.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In short, the corresponding outer MAC unicast DA, if not known, is replaced by a multicast DA, and when a response is received, the SA of that response now tells us the DA to use to reach the non-participating node that sourced the response. e.g., node 7 learns that C is reached by node 5.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since we wish to group/scope sets of non-participating ports into services and prevent them from multicasting to each other, IEEE 802.1aq provides a mechanism for per-source, per-service multicast forwarding and defines a special multicast destination address format to provide this.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since the multicast address must uniquely identify the tree, and because there is a tree per source per unique service, the multicast address contains two components: a service component in the low-order 24 bits and a network-wide unique identifier in the upper 22 bits.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since this is a multicast address, the multicast bit is set, and since we are not using the standard OUI space for these manufactured addresses, the Local 'L' bit is set to disambiguate these addresses.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] In Figure 3 above, this is represented with the DA=[7,O] where the 7 represents packets originating from node 7 and the colored O represents the E-LAN service we are scoped within.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Prior to creating multicast forwarding for a service, nodes with ports that face that service must be told they are members.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] For example, nodes 7, 4, 5 and 6 are told they are members of the given service, for example, service 200, and further that they should be using BVID 101.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This is advertised by ISIS and all nodes then do the SPBM computation to determine if they are participating either as a head end or tail end, or a tandem point between other head and tail ends in the service.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Since node 0 is a tandem between nodes 7 and 5, it creates a forwarding entry for packets from node 7 on this service, to node 5.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Likewise, since it is a tandem between nodes 7 and 4 it creates forwarding state from node 7 for packets in this service to node 4.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] This results in a true multicast entry where the DA/VID has outputs on two interfaces, 1 and 2.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] Node 2, on the other hand, is only on one shortest path in this service and only creates a single forwarding entry from node 7 to node 6 for packets in this service.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p01] The only real limiting factors are the FIB table sizes and computational power of the individual devices, both of which are growing yearly in leaps and bounds.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] 802.1aq takes IS-IS topology information augmented with service attachment (I-SID) information, does a series of computations and produces a forwarding table (filtering table) for unicast and multicast entries.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The IS-IS extensions that carry the information required by 802.1aq are given in the **isis-layer2** IETF document listed below.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] An implementation of 802.1aq will first modify the IS-IS hellos to include an NLPID (network layer protocol identifier) of 0xC01 in their Protocols-Supported type–length–value (TLV) (type 129) which has been reserved for 802.1aq.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The hellos also must include an MSTID (which gives the purpose of each VID), and finally, each ECMT behavior must be assigned to a VID and exchanged in the hellos.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] Note that NLPID of IP is not required to form an adjacency for 802.1aq, but also will not prevent an adjacency when present.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The links are assigned 802.1aq specific metrics, which travel in their own TLV (Type Length Value), which is more or less identical to the IP link metrics.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The calculations will always use the maximum of the two unidirectional link metrics to enforce symmetric route weights.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The node is assigned a MAC address to identify it globally, and this is used to form the IS-IS SYSID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] A box mac would normally serve this purpose.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The Area-Id is not directly used by 802.1aq but should, of course, be the same for nodes in the same 802.1aq network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] Multiple areas/levels are not yet supported.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The node is further assigned an SPSourceID, which is a 20-bit network-wide unique identifier.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This can often be the low 20 bits of the SYSID (if unique) or can be dynamically negotiated or manually configured.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The SPSourceID and the ECMT assignments to B-VIDs are then advertised into the IS-IS network in their own 802.1aq TLV.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The 802.1aq computations are restricted to links between nodes that have an 802.1aq link weight and that support the NLPID 0xC01.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] As previously discussed, the link weights are forced to be symmetric for the purpose of computation by taking the min of two dissimilar values.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] When a service is configured in the form of an I-SID assignment to an ECMT behavior, that I-SID is then advertised along with the desired ECMT behavior and an indication of its transmit, receive properties (a new TLV is used for this purpose of course).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] When an 802.1aq node receives an IS-IS update, it will compute the unique shortest path to all other IS-IS nodes that support 802.1aq.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] There will be one unique (symmetric) shortest path per ECMT behavior.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The tie breaking used to enforce this uniqueness and ECMT is described below.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The unicast FDB/FIB will be populated based on this first shortest path computation.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] There will be one entry per ECMT behavior/B-VID produced.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The above pseudocode computes many more SPF's than strictly necessary in most cases, and better algorithms are known to decide if a node is on a shortest path between two other nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] A reference to a paper presented at the IEEE, which gives a much faster algorithm that drastically reduces the number of outer iterations required, is given below.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] In general, though, even the exhaustive algorithm above is more than able to handle several hundred-node networks in a few tens of milliseconds on the 1 GHz or greater common CPUs when carefully crafted.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] For ISIDs that have chosen head-end replication, the computation is trivial and involves simply finding the other attachment points that receive that ISID and creating a serial unicast table to replicate to them one by one.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] 802.1aq must produce deterministic symmetric downstream congruent shortest paths.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This means that not only must a given node compute the same path forward and reverse, but all the other nodes downstream (and upstream) on that path must also produce the same result.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This downstream congruence is a consequence of the hop-by-hop forwarding nature of Ethernet since only the destination address and VID are used to decide the next hop.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] It is important to keep this in mind when trying to design other ECMT algorithms for 802.1aq, as this is an easy trap to fall into.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] It begins by taking the unidirectional link metrics that are advertised by ISIS for 802.1aq and ensuring that they are symmetric.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This is done by simply taking the MIN of the two values at both ends prior to doing any computations.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This alone does not guarantee symmetry, however.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The 802.1aq standard describes a mechanism called a PATHID, which is a network-wide unique identifier for a path.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This is a useful logical way to understand how to deterministically break ties but is not how one would implement such a tie-breaker in practice.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The PATHID is defined as just the sequence of SYSIDs that make up the path (not including the end points).. sorted.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] Every path in the network therefore has a unique PATHID independent of where in the network the path is discovered.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] 802.1aq always picks the lowest PATHID path when a choice presents itself in the shortest path computations.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This ensures that every node will make the same decision.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] For example, in Figure 7 above, there are four equal-cost paths between node 7 and node 5 as shown by the colors blue, green, pink and brown.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The lowest PATHID is therefore the brown path {0,1}.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This low PATHID algorithm has very desirable properties.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The first is that it can be done progressively by simply looking for the lowest SYSID along a path, and secondly, because an efficient implementation that operates stepwise is possible by simply back-tracking two competing paths and looking for the minimum of the two paths' minimum SYSIDs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The low PATHID algorithm is the basis of all 802.1aq tie breaking.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] ECMT is also based on the low PATHID algorithm by simply feeding it different SYSID permutations – one per ECMT algorithm.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The most obvious permutation to pass is a complete inversion of the SYSID by XOR-ing it with 0xfff... prior to looking for the min of two minimums.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This algorithm is referred to as high PATHID because it logically chooses the largest PATHID path when presented with two equal-cost choices.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] In the example in figure 7, the path with the highest PATHID is therefore the blue path whose PATHID is {2,3}.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] Simply inverting all the SYSIDs and running the low PATHID algorithm will yield the same result.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The other 14 defined ECMT algorithms use different permutations of the SYSID by XOR-ing it with different bit masks, which are designed to create a relatively good distribution of bits.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] It should be clear that different permutations will result in the purple and green paths being lowest in turn.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The 17 individual 64-bit masks used by the ECT algorithm are made up of the same byte value repeated eight times to fill each 64-bit mask.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] ECT-MASK[0] is reserved for a common spanning tree algorithm, while ECT-MASK[1] creates the Low PATHID set of shortest path first trees, ECT-MASK[2] creates the High PATHID set of shortest path trees, and the other indexes create other relatively diverse permutations of shortest path first trees.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] In additio,n the ECMT tie-breaking algorithms also permit some degree of human override or tweaking.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] This is accomplished by including a BridgePriority field together with the SYSID such that the combination, called a BridgeIdentifier, becomes the input to the ECT algorithm.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] By adjusting the BridgePriority up or down, a path's PATHID can be raised or lowered relative to others, and a substantial degree of tunability is afforded.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] The first public interoperability tests of IEEE 802.1aq were held in Ottawa in October 2010.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] Two vendors provided SPBM implementations, and a total of 5 physical switches and 32 emulated switches were tested for control/data and OA&M.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/ieee-802-1aq-p02] Further events were held in Ottawa in January 2011 with 5 vendors and 6 implementations, at 2013's Interop event at Las Vegas where an SPBM network was used as a backbone.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The **Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol** (**MSTP**) and algorithm, provides both simple and full connectivity assigned to any given virtual LAN (VLAN) throughout a bridged local area network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP uses bridge protocol data unit (BPDUs) to exchange information between spanning-tree compatible devices, to prevent loops in each Multiple Spanning Tree instance (MSTI) and in the Common and Internal Spanning Tree (CIST), by selecting active and blocked paths.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This is done as well as in Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) without the need of manually enabling backup links and getting rid of switching loop danger.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP allows frames assigned to different VLANs to follow separate paths, each based on an independent MSTI, within MST regions composed of local area networks (LANs) and MST bridges.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] These regions and the other bridges and LANs are connected into a single common spanning tree (CST).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] It was originally defined in IEEE 802.1s as an amendment to 802.1Q, 1998 edition, and later merged into IEEE 802.1Q-2005 Standard, and clearly defines an extension or an evolution of Radia Perlman's Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) and the Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] It has some similarities with Cisco Systems' Multiple Instances Spanning Tree Protocol (MISTP), but there are some differences.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The original STP and RSTP work on the physical link level, preventing bridge loops when redundant paths are present.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] However, when a LAN is virtualized using VLAN trunking, each physical link represents multiple logical connections.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Blocking a physical link blocks all its logical links and forces all traffic through the remaining physical links within the spanning tree.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Redundant links cannot be utilized at all.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Moreover, without careful network design, seemingly redundant links on the physical level may be used to connect *different* VLANs and blocking any of them may disconnect one or more VLANs, causing *bad paths*.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Instead, MSTP provides a potentially better utilization of alternate paths by enabling the use of alternate spanning trees for different VLANs or groups of VLANs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] As MSTP enables grouping and mapping VLANs into different spanning tree instances, there is an urge to determine a group or set of VLANs that are all using the same spanning tree; this is an MSTI.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Each instance defines a single forwarding topology for an exclusive set of VLANs; by contrast, STP or RSTP networks contain only a single spanning tree instance for the entire network, which contains all the VLANs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] While each MSTI can have multiple VLANs, each VLAN can be associated with only one MSTI.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] An MSTI is unable to span across MST regions because of its inherent locality to a single MST region.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This is done by an identifying number for each MSTI.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] For achieving the task of assigning each bridge to a region, each switch/bridge must compare its **MST Configuration Identifiers (Format Selector, Region Name, Revision Level and Configuration Digest)**, either of which represents VLAN to MSTIs mapping for each bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The role of the Common Spanning Tree (CST) in a network, and the Common and Internal Spanning Tree (CIST) configured on each device, is to prevent loops within a wider network that may span more than one MSTP Region and parts of the network running in legacy STP or RSTP mode.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The main function of bridge protocol data units (BPDUs) is to enable MSTP to select its root bridges for the proper CIST and each MSTI.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP includes all its spanning tree information in a single BPDU format.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Not only does it reduce the number of BPDUs required on a LAN to communicate spanning tree information for each VLAN, but it also ensures backward compatibility with RSTP (and, in effect, classic STP too).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] BPDUs' general format comprises a common generic portion, octets 1 to 36, that are based on those defined in IEEE Standard 802.1D, 2004, followed by components that are specific to CIST, octets 37 to 102.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Components specific to each MSTI are added to this BPDUs data block.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] In case there is an allocation of VIDs (VLAN IDs) into an MST Region which differs within the different bridges that compose it, **frames for some VIDs might be duplicated or even not delivered to some LANs at all**.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] To avoid this, MST Bridges check that they are allocating VIDs to the same spanning trees as their neighboring MST Bridges in the same Region by transmitting and receiving MST Configuration Identifiers along with the spanning tree information.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This object is specific and unique to MSTP; neither STP nor RSTP uses it.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP configures for every VLAN a single spanning tree active topology in a manner that there's at least one data route between any two end stations, eliminating data loops.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] It specifies various *objects* allowing the algorithm to operate in a proper way.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The different bridges in the various VLANs start advertising their own configuration to other bridges using the MST Configuration Identifier in order to allocate frames with given VIDs (VLAN ID) to any of the different MSTIs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] A priority vector is utilized to construct the CIST; it connects all the bridges and LANs in a Bridged LAN and ensures that paths within each region are always preferred to paths outside the Region.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Besides, there is an MSTI priority vector, which comprises the necessary information to build up a deterministic and independently manageable active topology for any given MSTI within each region.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Additionally, comparisons and calculations done by each bridge select a CIST priority vector for each Port (based on priority vectors, MST Configuration Identifiers and on an incremental Path Cost associated with each receiving port).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This leads to one bridge being selected as the CIST Root of the Bridged LAN; then, a minimum cost path to the root is shifted out for each Bridge and LANs (thus preventing loops and ensuring full connectivity between VLANs).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Subsequently, in each region, the bridge whose minimum cost path to the root doesn't pass through another bridge with the same MST Conf.ID will be identified as its Region's CIST Regional Root.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Conversely, each Bridge whose minimum cost path to the Root is through a Bridge using the same MST Configuration Identifier is identified as being in the same MST Region as that Bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] In summary, MSTP encodes some additional information in its BPDU regarding region information and configuration; each of these messages conveys the spanning tree information for each instance.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Each instance can be assigned several configured VLANs; frames (packets) assigned to these VLANs operate in this spanning tree instance whenever they are inside the MST region.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] To avoid conveying their entire VLAN to spanning tree mapping in each BPDU, bridges encode an MD5 digest of their VLAN to the instance table in the MSTP BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This digest is then used by other MSTP bridges, along with other administratively configured values, to determine if the neighboring bridge is in the same MST region as itself.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP is designed to be STP and RSTP compatible and interoperable without additional operational management practice.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This is due to a set of measurements based on RSTP (Clause 17 of IEEE Std 802.1D, 2004 Edition), intending to provide the capability for frames assigned to different VLANs to be transmitted along different paths within MST Regions.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Into the bargain, they also share some problems, such as: MSTP can't protect against temporary loops caused by the inter-connection of two LAN segments by devices other than the Bridges that operate invisibly with respect to support of the Bridges' MAC Internal Sublayer Service.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] For all the above, it can be concluded that MSTP is fully compatible with RSTP bridges; an MSTP BPDU can be interpreted by an RSTP bridge as an RSTP BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This not only allows compatibility with RSTP bridges without configuration changes, but also causes any RSTP bridges outside of an MSTP Region to see the region as a single RSTP bridge, regardless of the number of MSTP bridges inside the region itself.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This section is mainly oriented to provide any user with a proper manner of configuring an MSTP network over Cisco devices.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Be sure of having configured VLANs and having associated them with switch ports.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Afterwards, determine: MSTP Regions, revision level and instances; which VLANs and switch ports will belong to which MSTIs, and, finally, which devices do you want to be root bridges for each MSTI.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Common and Internal Spanning Tree (CIST) is the default spanning tree instance for MSTP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This means that all VLANs that are not explicitly configured into another MSTI are members of the CIST.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The software supports a single instance of the MSTP Algorithm consisting of the CIST and up to 15 MSTIs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] A VLAN can only be mapped to one MSTI or to the CIST.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] One VLAN mapped to multiple spanning trees is not allowed.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] All the VLANs are mapped to the CIST by default.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Once a VLAN is mapped to a specified MSTI, it is removed from the CIST.To avoid unnecessary STP processing, a port that is attached to a LAN with no other bridges or switches attached can be configured as an edge port.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The first skel of this protocol was proposed in.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] AMSTP is a simplified one-tree instance rooted at each edge bridge in the core to forward frames.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] To set up these trees, AMSTP relies on one basic tree, which will be used to obtain instances (named Alternate Multiple Spanning Tree Instances – AMSTI), until one of them is built per switch for the network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The process applied to build up the main/basic tree is the same as in RSTP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] In summary, firstly, a bridge must be elected as the Root Bridge (this is done by the emission of BPDUs from each switch on the network periodically, every Hello Time, and selecting the lowest Bridge ID).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Then, every switch will compute and calculate its cost to the Root Bridge and, afterwards, the root ports must be elected by selecting the one that receives the best BPDU, that is, the one that announces the minimum path cost to the root bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] AMSTP BPDUs use the same local multicast protocol addresses as STP and have a structure that resembles MSTP BPDUs since both are composed essentially of a basic BPDU and several AM-Records, allowing full backwards compatibility with RSTP and STP standard protocols.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Each of the AM-Records contains the data used to negotiate a specific tree instance (AMSTI).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Every ABridge, except for the elected root bridge, creates an AM-Record for its own spanning tree instances.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] They are used by connected ports of neighboring switches to negotiate the transitions of each tree instance with a proposal/agreement mechanism.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This protocol, developed in emphasizes in terms of efficiency in network usage and path length.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] That's the main reason why it uses AMSTP, a simplified and self-configuring version of MSTP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Abridges can be described as a two-tiered hierarchy of layer-two switches in which network islands running independent rapid spanning tree protocols communicate through a core formed by island root bridges (ABridges).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] As it has been mentioned, it is focused on efficiency, this is due to the ability of AMSTP to provide optimum paths in the core mesh and the usage of RSTP to efficiently aggregate the traffic at island networks.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Its convergence speed is as fast as RSTP and MSTP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] With the objective of enhancing the properties of Abridges protocol, a two-level hierarchical link layer infrastructure in which segmentation is performed at the link layer is proposed.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The core will be composed primarily of Abridges (bridges using an implementation of AMSTP) and will oversee connecting the leaf access networks that are referred to as *access layer*.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Besides, each of these access networks, also called islands, is a layer-two sub-network using STP connected to one or more Abridges.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Inside every island or access network, a bridge is automatically elected to behave as the Root Bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This one bridge will behave as a gateway, allowing the forwarding of frames from the core to an island and conversely.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Just one Abridge is going to perform these gateway functions, although many could be connected.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Communication among 802.1D bridges and between standard 802.1D bridges and ABridges does not require point-to-point connections.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The ABridge receiving an ARP frame from an island host obtains the island in which the destination is located by asking an ARP server where the host was previously registered by its island ABridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This server stores the IP to MAC mapping and the island ABridge ID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The ARP servers distribute their load based on hashing of the IP addresses served.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] The core self-configures, and the operation is transparent to all hosts and standard switches at islands.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Abridges will configure each of their ports to be part either of the core or of an island.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This port self-configuration is done with very simple stipulations: if a port is not connected to another Abridge using a point-to-point link, it will turn itself into an access port; on the other hand, ports directly connected to another Abridge are configured as core ports.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] This auto-configuration mechanism is pretty like the one used in RSTP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] Like any layer-two-based protocol, ABridges uses ARP broadcasts to obtain the link-layer address associated with an IP address on the same LAN or VLAN.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/multiple-spanning-tree-protocol] That is the main reason why avoiding overflooding is a matter of paramount priority; to limit this broadcast traffic, it is recommended to use distributed load ARP servers, although their use is not compulsory.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The **Spanning Tree Protocol**(**STP**) is a network protocol that builds a loop-free logical topology for Ethernet networks.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The basic function of STP is to prevent bridge loops and the broadcast radiation that results from them.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Spanning tree also allows a network design to include backup links providing fault tolerance if an active link fails.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] As the name suggests, STP creates a spanning tree that characterizes the relationship of nodes within a network of connected layer-2 bridges, and disables those links that are not part of the spanning tree, leaving a single active path between any two network nodes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] STP is based on an algorithm that was invented by Radia Perlman while she was working for Digital Equipment Corporation.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In 2001, the IEEE introduced **Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol** (**RSTP**) as 802.1w.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP provides significantly faster recovery in response to network changes or failures, introducing new convergence behaviors and bridge port roles to do this.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP was designed to be backwards-compatible with standard STP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] STP was originally standardized as IEEE 802.1D but the functionality of spanning tree (802.1D), rapid spanning tree (802.1w), and Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (802.1s) has since been incorporated into IEEE 802.1Q-2014.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] While STP is still in use today, in many modern networks its primary use is as a loop-protection mechanism rather than a fault tolerance mechanism.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Link aggregation protocols such as LACP bond multiple links to provide link-level fault tolerance while simultaneously increasing overall link capacity.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] However, implementing switch-level redundancy requires multi-chassis link aggregation, of which only proprietary variants exist.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Shortest Path Bridging combines both loop-free forwarding and link aggregation, but hasn't reached STP's or LACP's popularity yet, as of 2026.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] with Spanning Tree Protocol implementation in a local area network (LAN).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] After link failure, the spanning tree algorithm computes and spans a new least-cost tree.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The need for the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) arose because switches in local area networks (LANs) are often interconnected using redundant links to improve resilience should one connection fail.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] However, this connection configuration creates a switching loop resulting in broadcast radiations and MAC table instability.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] If redundant links are used to connect switches, then switching loops need to be avoided.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] To avoid the problems associated with redundant links in a switched LAN, STP is implemented on switches to monitor the network topology.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Every link between switches, and in particular redundant links, is catalogued.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The spanning-tree algorithm then blocks forwarding on redundant links by setting up one preferred link between switches in the LAN.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] This preferred link is used for all Ethernet frames unless it fails, in which case a non-preferred redundant link is enabled.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] When implemented in a network, STP designates one layer-2 switch as *root bridge*.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] All switches then select their best connection towards the root bridge for forwarding and block other redundant links.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] All switches constantly communicate with their neighbors in the LAN using § Bridge protocol data units (BPDUs).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Provided there is more than one link between two switches, the STP root bridge calculates the cost of each path based on bandwidth.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] STP will select the path with the lowest cost, that is, the highest bandwidth, as the preferred link.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] STP will enable this preferred link as the only path to be used for Ethernet frames between the two switches, and disable all other possible links by designating the switch ports that connect the preferred path as *root port*.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] After STP-enabled switches in a LAN have elected the root bridge, all non-root bridges assign one of their ports as a root port.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] This is either the port that connects the switch to the root bridge, or if there are several paths, the port with the preferred path as calculated by the root bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Because not all switches are directly connected to the root bridge, they communicate amongst each other using STP BPDUs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Each switch adds the cost of its own path to the cost received from the neighboring switches to determine the total cost of a given path to the root bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Once the cost of all possible paths to the root bridge has been added up, each switch assigns a port as a root port that connects to the path with the lowest cost, or highest bandwidth, that will eventually lead to the root bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The STP path cost default was originally calculated by the formula ⁠1 Gbit/s/bandwidth⁠.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] When faster speeds became available, the default values were adjusted as otherwise speeds above 1 Gbit/s would have been indistinguishable by STP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Its successor RSTP uses a similar formula with a larger numerator: ⁠20 Tbit/s/bandwidth⁠.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] These formulas lead to the sample values in the table.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] All switch ports in the LAN where STP is enabled are categorized.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] A port that would cause a switching loop if it were active.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] To prevent the use of looped paths, no user data is sent or received over a blocking port.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] BPDU data is still received in the blocking state.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] A blocked port may go into forwarding mode if the other links in use fail and the spanning tree algorithm determines that the port may transition to the forwarding state.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The switch processes BPDUs and awaits possible new information that would cause it to return to the blocking state.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] While the port does not yet forward frames, it does learn source addresses from frames received and adds them to the MAC table.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] A port in normal operation receiving and forwarding frames.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The port monitors incoming BPDUs that would indicate it should return to the blocking state to prevent a loop.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] A network administrator has manually disabled the switch port.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] When a device is first attached to a switch port, it will not immediately start to forward data.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] It will instead go through a number of states while it processes BPDUs and determines the topology of the network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The port attached to a host such as a computer, printer or server always goes into the forwarding state, albeit after a delay of about 30 seconds while it goes through the listening and learning states.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The time spent in the listening and learning states is determined by a value known as the forward delay (default 15 seconds and set by the root bridge).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] If another switch is connected, the port may remain in blocking mode if it is determined that it would cause a loop in the network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Topology change notification (TCN) BPDUs are used to inform other switches of port changes.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] TCNs are injected into the network by a non-root switch and propagated to the root.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Upon receipt of the TCN, the root switch will set the topology change flag in its normal BPDUs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] This flag is propagated to all other switches and instructs them to rapidly age out their forwarding table entries.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Before configuring STP, the network topology should be carefully planned.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Basic configuration requires that STP be enabled on all switches in the LAN and the same version of STP chosen on each.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The administrator may determine which switch will be the root bridge and configure the switches appropriately.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] If the root bridge goes down, the protocol will automatically assign a new root bridge based on bridge ID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] If all switches have the same bridge ID, such as the default ID, and the root bridge goes down, a tie situation arises and the protocol will assign one switch as the root bridge based on the switch's MAC addresses.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Once the switches have been assigned a bridge ID and the protocol has chosen the root bridge switch, the best path to the root bridge is calculated based on port cost, path cost and port priority.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Ultimately, STP calculates the path cost on the basis of the bandwidth of a link.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Administrators can influence the protocol's choice of the preferred path by configuring the port cost; the lower the port cost, the more likely it is that the protocol will choose the connected link as root port for the preferred path.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The selection of how other switches in the topology choose their root port, or the least cost path to the root bridge, can be influenced by the port priority.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The highest priority will mean the path will ultimately be less preferred.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] If all ports of a switch have the same priority, the port with the lowest number is chosen to forward frames.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The *root bridge* of the spanning tree is the bridge with the smallest (lowest) bridge ID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Each bridge has a configurable priority number and a MAC address; the bridge ID is the concatenation of the bridge priority and the MAC address.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The bridge priority default is 32,768 and can be configured only in multiples of 4096.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] When comparing two bridge IDs, the priority portions are compared first and the MAC addresses are compared only if the priorities are equal.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The switch with the lowest priority of all the switches will be the root; if there is a tie, then the switch with the lowest priority and lowest MAC address will be the root.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] If the network administrators would like switch *B* to become the root bridge, they must set its priority to be less than 32,768.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] When multiple paths from a bridge are least-cost paths, the chosen path uses the neighbor bridge with the lower bridge ID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The root port is thus the one connecting to the bridge with the lowest bridge ID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] d instead of segment f, there would be two paths of length 2 to the root, one path going through bridge 24 and the other through bridge 92.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Because there are two least-cost paths, the lower bridge ID (24) would be used as the tiebreaker in choosing which path to use.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] When more than one bridge on a segment leads to a least-cost path to the root, the bridge with the lower bridge ID is used to forward messages to the root.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In the figures, there are two least-cost paths from network segment d to the root, one going through bridge 24 and the other through bridge 92.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The lower bridge ID is 24, so the tiebreaker dictates that the designated port is the port through which network segment d is connected to bridge 24.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] If bridge IDs were equal, then the bridge with the lowest MAC address would have the designated port.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In either case, the loser sets the port as being blocked.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] When the root bridge has more than one port on a single network segment, the bridge ID is effectively tied, as are all root path costs (all equal zero).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The port on that network segment with the lowest port ID becomes the designated port.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] It is put into forwarding mode while all other ports on the root bridge on that same network segment become non-designated ports and are put into blocking mode.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Not all bridge manufacturers follow this rule, instead making all root bridge ports designated ports, and putting them all in forwarding mode.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In some cases, there may still be a tie, as when the root bridge has multiple active ports on the same network segment (see above) with equally low root path costs and bridge IDs, or, in other cases, multiple bridges are connected by multiple cables and multiple ports.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In each case, a single bridge may have multiple candidates for its root port.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In these cases, candidates for the root port have already received BPDUs offering equally-low (i.e. the "best") root path costs and equally-low (i.e. the "best") bridge IDs, and the final tiebreaker goes to the port that received the lowest (i.e. the "best") port priority ID, or port ID.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The above rules describe one way of determining what spanning tree will be computed by the algorithm, but the rules as written require knowledge of the entire network.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The bridges have to determine the root bridge and compute the port roles (root, designated, or blocked) with only the information that they have.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] To ensure that each bridge has enough information, the bridges use special data frames called bridge protocol data units (BPDUs) to exchange information about the Spanning Tree Protocol, bridge IDs, and root path costs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] , and may be used instead of the standard.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] A bridge sends a BPDU frame using the unique MAC address of the port itself as a source address.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Combined length of the LLC Header, BPDU payload, and FCS.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] BPDUs are exchanged regularly (every 2 seconds by default) and enable switches to keep track of network changes and to start and stop forwarding at ports as required.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] To prevent the delay when connecting hosts to a switch and during some topology changes, Rapid STP was developed, which allows a switch port to rapidly transition into the forwarding state during these situations.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] There are two types of BPDUs in the original STP specification (802.1D) (the Rapid Spanning Tree (RSTP) extension uses a specific RSTP BPDU).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Topology change notification (TCN) BPDU, used to announce changes in the network topology, such as port up or port down.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] 0 (unused) or 1 for Proposal in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] 01 for Port Role Alternate/Backup in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] 10 for Port Role Root in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] 11 for Port Role Designated in RST/MST/SPT BPD.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] 0 (unused) or 1 for Learning in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] 0 (unused) or 1 for Forwarding in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] 0 (unused) or 1 for Agreement in RST/MST/SPT BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] 0 or 1 for Topology Change Acknowledgement.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Configuration BPDU (CBPDU), used for spanning tree computation and sent by root bridges to provide information to all switches.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The first Spanning Tree Protocol was invented in 1985 at the Digital Equipment Corporation by Radia Perlman.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In 1990, the IEEE published the first standard for the protocol as 802.1D, based on the algorithm designed by Perlman.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Subsequent versions were published in 1998 and 2004, incorporating various extensions.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The original Perlman-inspired Spanning Tree Protocol, called DEC STP, is not a standard and differs from the IEEE version in message format as well as timer settings.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Some bridges implement both the IEEE and the DEC versions of the Spanning Tree Protocol, but their interworking can create issues for the network administrator.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Different implementations of a standard are not guaranteed to interoperate, due, for example, to differences in default timer settings.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The IEEE encourages vendors to provide a Protocol Implementation Conformance Statement, declaring which capabilities and options have been implemented, to help users determine whether different implementations will interoperate correctly.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In 2001, the IEEE introduced Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP) as **IEEE 802.1w**.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP was then incorporated into IEEE 802.1D-2004, making the original STP standard obsolete.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP was designed to be backward-compatible with standard STP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] RSTP provides significantly faster spanning tree convergence after a topology change, introducing new convergence behaviors and bridge port roles to accomplish this.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] While STP can take 30 to 50 seconds to respond to a topology change, RSTP is typically able to respond to changes within 3 × *hello times* (default: 3 × 2 seconds) or within a few milliseconds of a physical link failure.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The hello time is an important and configurable time interval that is used by RSTP for several purposes; its default value is 2 seconds.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] STP and RSTP do not segregate switch ports by VLAN.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] However, in Ethernet switched environments where multiple VLANs exist, it is often desirable to create multiple spanning trees so that traffic on different VLANs uses different links.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Before the IEEE published a Spanning Tree Protocol standard for VLANs, a number of vendors who sold VLAN-capable switches developed their own Spanning Tree Protocol versions that were VLAN capable.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Cisco developed, implemented and published the **Per-VLAN Spanning Tree** (**PVST**) proprietary protocol using its own proprietary Inter-Switch Link (ISL) for VLAN encapsulation, and PVST+ which uses 802.1Q VLAN encapsulation.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Both standards implement a separate spanning tree for every VLAN.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Cisco switches now commonly implement PVST+ and can only implement Spanning Trees for VLANs if the other switches in the LAN implement the same VLAN STP protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] HP provides PVST and PVST+ compatibility in some of its network switches.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Some devices from Force10 Networks, Alcatel-Lucent, Extreme Networks, Avaya, Brocade Communications Systems and BLADE Network Technologies support PVST+.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Extreme Networks does so with two limitations: Lack of support on ports where the VLAN is untagged/native, and also on the VLAN with ID 1.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The switch vendor Juniper Networks in turn developed and implemented its VLAN Spanning Tree Protocol (VSTP) to provide compatibility with Cisco's PVST, so that the switches from both vendors can be included in one LAN.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The VSTP protocol is only supported by the EX and MX Series from Juniper Networks.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] If this protocol is in use, VLAN membership for trunk interfaces must be statically configured.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] By default, VSTP uses the RSTP protocol as its core spanning-tree protocol, but usage of STP can be forced if the network includes old bridges.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] More information about configuring VSTP on Juniper Networks switches was published in the official documentation.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Cisco also published a proprietary version of Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] It creates a spanning tree for each VLAN, just like PVST.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Cisco refers to this as **Rapid Per-VLAN Spanning Tree** (**RPVST**).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (MSTP), originally defined in IEEE 802.1s-2002 and later merged into IEEE 802.1Q-2005, defines an extension to RSTP to further develop the usefulness of VLANs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In the standard, a spanning tree that maps one or more VLANs is called a *multiple spanning tree* (MST).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Under MSTP, a spanning tree can be defined for individual VLANs or for groups of VLANs.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Furthermore, the administrator can define alternate paths within a spanning tree.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Switches are first assigned to an MST region, then VLANs are mapped against or assigned to this MST.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] A *common spanning tree* (CST) is an MST to which several VLANs are mapped; this group of VLANs is called *MST instance* (MSTI).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] CSTs are backward compatible with the STP and RSTP standards.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] A MST that has only one VLAN assigned to it is an *internal spanning tree* (IST).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Unlike some proprietary per-VLAN spanning tree implementations, MSTP includes all of its spanning tree information in a single BPDU format.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Not only does this reduce the number of BPDUs required to communicate spanning tree information for each VLAN, but it also ensures backward compatibility with RSTP and, in effect, classic STP too.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP does this by encoding an additional region of information after the standard RSTP BPDU as well as a number of MSTI messages (from 0 to 64 instances, although in practice many bridges support fewer).
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Each of these MSTI configuration messages conveys the spanning tree information for each instance.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Each instance can be assigned a number of configured VLANs and frames assigned to these VLANs operate in this spanning tree instance whenever they are inside the MST region.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In order to avoid conveying their entire VLAN to spanning tree mapping in each BPDU, bridges encode an MD5 digest of their VLAN to the instance table in the MSTP BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] MSTP is fully compatible with RSTP bridges in that an MSTP BPDU can be interpreted by an RSTP bridge as an RSTP BPDU.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] This not only allows compatibility with RSTP bridges without configuration changes but also causes any RSTP bridges outside of an MSTP region to see the region as a single RSTP bridge, regardless of the number of MSTP bridges inside the region itself.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In order to further facilitate this view of an MSTP region as a single RSTP bridge, the MSTP protocol uses a variable known as remaining hops as a time-to-live counter instead of the message age timer used by RSTP.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The message age time is only incremented once when spanning-tree information enters an MST region, and therefore, RSTP bridges will see a region as only one *hop* in the spanning tree.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Ports at the edge of an MSTP region connected to either an RSTP or STP bridge or an endpoint are known as boundary ports.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] As in RSTP, these ports can be configured as edge ports to facilitate rapid changes to the forwarding state when connected to endpoints.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] SPB consolidates multiple existing functionalities, including Spanning Tree Protocol (STP), Multiple Spanning Tree Protocol (MSTP), Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP), Link aggregation, and Multiple MAC Registration Protocol (MMRP) into a one link state protocol.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The bridge ID (BID) is a field inside a BPDU packet.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The first two bytes are the bridge priority, an unsigned integer of 0–65,535.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] The last six bytes are a MAC address supplied by the bridge.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Prior to IEEE 802.1D-2004, the first two bytes gave a 16-bit bridge priority.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Since IEEE 802.1D-2004, the first four bits are a configurable priority, and the last twelve bits carry the bridge system ID extension.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] In the case of MST, the bridge system ID extension carries the MSTP instance number.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Some vendors set the bridge system ID extension to carry a VLAN ID, allowing a different spanning tree per VLAN, such as Cisco's PVST.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Spanning tree is an older protocol with a longer convergence time.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Improper use or implementation can contribute to network disruptions.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Blocking links is a crude approach to high availability and preventing loops.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Modern networks can make use of all connected links by use of protocols that inhibit, control or suppress the natural behavior of logical or physical topology loops.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Newer, more robust protocols include the TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) protocol, also created by Perlman, and Shortest Path Bridging from the IEEE.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Configuring connections between network equipment as layer-3 IP links and relying on IP routing for resiliency and to prevent loops is a popular alternative.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Switch virtualization techniques like Cisco Virtual Switching System and Virtual PortChannel and HP Intelligent Resilient Framework combine multiple switches into a single logical entity.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Such a multi-chassis link aggregation group works like a normal port trunk, only distributed through multiple switches.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] Conversely, partitioning technologies compartmentalize a single physical chassis into multiple logical entities.
[src:spanning-tree-protocol/rapid-spanning-tree-protocol] On the edge of the network, loop detection is configured to prevent accidental loops by users.
